The utility function `largestBSTUtil` recursively traverses the binary tree in post order. When there is no root node, it returns a `TreeInfo` structure with default values. The function then checks the left and right subtrees.

The function checks if both the left and right subtrees are BST, and if the current root node's value is greater than the maximum value of its left subtree and less than the minimum value of its right subtree. If this condition is true, it sets `largestBST` as the maximum of its previous value and the sum of the current node's left and right subtree sizes plus one (the current node).

The function then returns a new `TreeInfo` structure with an updated `size`, `minValue`, and `maxValue` that combines information from both subtrees.

The base function `largestBSTSubtree` initializes an array `largestBST` at zero and calls the `largestBSTUtil` function. After the traversal, the `largestBST` will contain the size of the largest BST subtree found in the input binary tree. We return this value.

